a_0.informal problem:
Let $p(n)$ be a function defined as follows: 
$$
p(n) = \begin{cases}
3\cdot\left(\frac{2}{5}\right)^{n-3}\cdot\left(1-\frac{2}{5}\right)^3, & n=5 \\
\left(\frac{2}{5}\right)^3\cdot\left(1-\frac{2}{5}\right)^{n-3}, & n=6 \\
0, & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$

Find the value of $p(5) + p(6)$. The final answer is $\frac{44}{125}$.
